{"title_page": "David Abrahams (businessman)", "text_new": "{{other people|David Abrahams}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n'''David Martin Abrahams''' (born 13 November 1944)<ref>http://www2.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=188215095&d=bmd_1390257354. https://books.google.com/books?id=hJc8afOZV0QC&pg=PA8&dq=abrahams,+david+martin&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VIMXU6LuEYabtAbS9IGgDw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=abrahams%2C%20david%20martin&f=false The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History (2011), p. 8. Company House records</ref> is an English entrepreneur, philanthropist and political activist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/43690/abrahams-bid-broker-peace-deal-0|title=Abrahams in bid to broker peace deal|last=Bright|first=Martin|date=14 January 2011|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAbrahams was born in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], and brought up in [[Whitley Bay]] as the only child in a strongly political family.<ref name=\"thejc.com\">http://www.thejc.com/business/business-features/28274/abrahams-my-%C2%A31bn-gift-north-east</ref><ref name=\"jc-20071130a\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867|title=Political Lives: David Abrahams|author=Alex Hunt|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 February 2014|accessdate=26 February 2014}}</ref> His father [[Bennie Abrahams]] (1906\u20131990) was a Labour councillor for the [[Monkchester]] ward of [[Newcastle City Council]], and served as the city's Lord Mayor for one year in 1981-2.<ref>https://www.newcastle.gov.uk/sites/default/files/wwwfileroot/your-council-and-democracy/councillors-and-democracy/lord_mayors_and_sheriffs_1974_to_date_1.pdf</ref>\n\nHis mother Marion Marcelline Abrahams was a concert hall violinist for the Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref> and a Labour councillor in Newcastle <ref>https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-jewish-chronicle/20071130/textview</ref>. Abrahams was educated at Ascham House preparatory school, now Newcastle School for Boys in Gosforth, and Rutherford Grammar School.  In 1977, Mohammed Ali paid a visit to the Abrahams family home in Gosforth, where his 105-year-old Grandmother Annie Abrahams chatted to him about the underprivileged <ref>https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/discover-how-muhammad-ali-dropped-11439578</ref>.  In July 1979, he accompanied his Grandmother aged 107 to meet the Queen at Buckingham Palace.\n\n==Political career==\n\nAbrahams was a councillor for the Labour Party on [[Tyne and Wear]] County Council for six years from 1979 to 1983 <ref name=\"channel4.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/who+is+david+abrahams/1105647.html|title=Who is David Abrahams? - Channel 4 News|website=www.channel4.com}}</ref>, and voted to bring the Nissan plant to Sunderland.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref>\nHe was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Richmond (Yorks) (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond, Yorkshire]] in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] but stood down after a failed deselection attempt by some members of the local party.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/archive/</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/nov/28/uk.partyfunding3|title=Profile: David Abrahams|first=Martin|last=Wainwright|date=28 November 2007|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hJc8afOZV0QC&pg=PA8&dq=abrahams,+david+martin&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VIMXU6LuEYabtAbS9IGgDw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=abrahams,+david+martin&f=false|title=The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History|first1=William D.|last1=Rubinstein|first2=Michael|last2=Jolles|first3=Hilary L.|last3=Rubinstein|date=22 February 2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|via=Google Books}}</ref>  In 1997 he was unsuccessful in his attempt at selection for the seat of [[Wansbeck]] near Newcastle.<ref name=\"channel4.com\"/>\n\nA close associate of [[Tony Blair]] and [[Lord Levy]] during the [[New Labour]]-era,<ref name=\"abrah\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/1571209/David-Abrahams-glory-days-as-Blair-ally.html|title=David Abrahams' glory days as Blair ally|date=2 December 2007|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Abrahams was associated with a number of Jewish and pro-Israel groups such as the [[Trade Union Friends of Israel]], the [[Community Security Trust]], the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and [[Academic Friends of Israel]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAbrahams faced high-profile media accusations in 2007 that he had secretly made \u00a3630,000 in donations to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7123236.stm|title=Abrahams makes proxy donor claim|date=1 December 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> by channelling the donations through four different individuals in what was thought to have been a breach of the electoral law on transparent disclosure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7114500.stm|title=David Abrahams and Labour donations row|date=2 December 2007|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The Donorgate scandal put pressure on then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] who set up an internal enquiry, although no report has ever been published.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/1570859/Hunt-for-mystery-benefactor-in-Gordon-Browns-donations-scandal.html|title=Hunt for 'mystery benefactor' in Gordon Brown's donations scandal|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=29 November 2007|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref> Abrahams was subsequently cleared of any wrongdoing by the police, according to a statement issued by his solicitor Louis Charalambous, a partner with the London law firm Simons Muirhead and Burton, in April 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/apr/28/justice.ukcrime|title=Police clear donor Abrahams|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=28 April 2008|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC spotlighted Abrahams in their 'Political Lives' series in February 2014, detailing his life's work.<ref name=\"Hunt\">{{cite news|last=Hunt|first=Alex|title=Political Lives: David Abrahams|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867|accessdate=28 February 2014|publisher=BBC|date=17 February 2014}}</ref> In the BBC interview footage he stated that \"I've been active politically all my life, still am and still taking an active interest in Labour \u2013 these things don't go away. But it's not the be all and end all, being in the Commons \u2013 people have still got the qualities, got the skills, still got the talent and use them in different directions.\"<ref name=\"Hunt\"/>\n\nIn April 2016, following high-profile remarks made by a Labour MP [[Naz Shah]] and the former [[Mayor of London]], [[Ken Livingstone]], Abrahams said that he would no longer financially support the Labour party, claiming it was becoming increasingly [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/north-east-labour-donor-said-11259541|title=North East Labour donor said he will give no cash to the party after anti-Semitism scandal|first=Sean|last=Seddon|date=28 April 2016|website=nechronicle}}</ref> In an article for the Guardian he accused the hard left of perverting the principles of social justice and liberal, progressive politics. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/30/labour-rediscover-liberal-values</ref> It has been claimed that he ended his Labour Party membership in late March 2018 because Labour under [[Jeremy Corbyn]] had failed to tackle the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/major-jewish-labour-donor-explains-why-he-has-quit-the-party-1.461586|title=Major Jewish Labour donor explains why he has quit the party|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> However, Abrahams was active in voicing his concerns about the candidates for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leadership election 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abrahams|first=David|url=https://twitter.com/davidabrahams8/status/1223791592177373184|title=Criticism of Labour Leader Candidates|date=2  Feb 2020|accessdate=6 Feb 2020}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Other Interests==\n\nAbrahams is a [[Freeman of the City of London]].\n\nIn 2010 it was reported that Abrahams had met senior Hamas officials including Palestinian Legislative Council speaker Aziz Dwaik<ref>https://www.thejc.com/news/israel/david-abrahams-meets-hamas-1.13585</ref> and had appeared to wrest a significant change in tone from the Palestinian leadership. He indicated that Hamas officials were prepared to accept \u2013 but not necessarily recognise \u2013 the existence of Israel, and they would be prepared to nullify the part of the Hamas charter that calls for the obliteration of Israel.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/jan/31/david-abrahams-interview</ref>\n\nHe became Vice President of Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) in 2010<ref>https://rusi.org/rusi-news/new-rusi-council</ref>, and subsequently its first global ambassador.  He serves on the Advisory Board of the Global Diplomatic Forum.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\nIn 2013 it was reported that he had donated two tranches of \u00a3250,000 to found a chair in International Politics of the Middle East at [[Warwick University]] from 2005.<ref>https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/labour-donors-cheques-warwick-university-3105529</ref>\n\nHe has also served as Vice-Chairman of the [[Jewish Labour Movement]], Acting Director of Labour Friends of Israel and on the Executive of the Trade Union Friends of Israel.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn 2010, it was reported that used to support \"more than 70 charitable and voluntary organisations, including male cancer research charity 'Every Man Alive'\".<ref name=\"thejc.com\"/>\n\nAbrahams' Twitter page is @davidabrahams 8, where he describes himself as \"working for peace in the Middle East and prosperity in the North East (UK)\".\n\nAbrahams has been an active supporter of peace initiatives in the Middle East. His diplomatic efforts in many Middle East countries brought him into contact with Yasser Arafat as well as Hamas and other leaders establishing grounds for ongoing dialogue.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\nSince 1968, he has been involved North East Prisons After Care Society (NEPACS).  He is currently a trustee and Board Member.\nHe is a former founder and Vice Chair of North East Alzheimer\u2019s Society and was for many years National Director of The Campaign For Pensioner Poverty.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref> He served for twelve years as a trustee and on the executive of The Council for Christians and Jews, becoming their Director of Parliamentary Affairs.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\n==Business==\nAbrahams founded the \u201cLondon Girl\u201d group of fashion shops and a chain of hotels in the north east.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref>\nIn 2009, Abrahams obtained planning permission to build a 540-acre business park, near Bowburn, outside Durham, with onsite connectivity to the main Edinburgh-London railway line and off Junction 61 on the A1(M). <ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4398717.go-ahead-1bn-durham-green-business-park/</ref> He said he would donate the profits from building the business park to \u201ccauses he has supported in the past\u201d.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4123635.abrahams-ill-give-profits-charity/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Abrahams was reported to be in  talks with 15 potential tenants for a 540-acre site on the edge of Durham.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/jan/31/david-abrahams-interview|title=Labour donor David Abrahams' gift to the north-east|date=31 January 2010|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>He was subsequently reported to be selling the site.<ref> http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/8517543.stm</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was reported that the Integra 61 project on the site would include industrial units, offices, a hotel, shops, gym, care home, pub and GP surgery. Persimmon Homes obtained permission to build up to 270 houses on the site.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/northdurham/17186008.details-emerge-170-house-development-integra-61-bowburn/</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that Amazon had taken a warehouse of almost 2 million square feet at the site from new owner Tritax Big Box REIT plc. <ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/business/17496504.new-contractor-announced-integra-61-set-house-huge-amazon-warehouse/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abrahams, David}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|David Abrahams}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n'''David Martin Abrahams''' (born 13 November 1944)<ref>http://www2.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=188215095&d=bmd_1390257354. https://books.google.com/books?id=hJc8afOZV0QC&pg=PA8&dq=abrahams,+david+martin&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VIMXU6LuEYabtAbS9IGgDw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=abrahams%2C%20david%20martin&f=false The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History (2011), p. 8. Company House records</ref> is an English entrepreneur, philanthropist and political activist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/43690/abrahams-bid-broker-peace-deal-0|title=Abrahams in bid to broker peace deal|last=Bright|first=Martin|date=14 January 2011|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAbrahams was born in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], and brought up in [[Whitley Bay]] as the only child in a strongly political family.<ref name=\"thejc.com\">http://www.thejc.com/business/business-features/28274/abrahams-my-%C2%A31bn-gift-north-east</ref><ref name=\"jc-20071130a\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867|title=Political Lives: David Abrahams|author=Alex Hunt|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 February 2014|accessdate=26 February 2014}}</ref> His father [[Bennie Abrahams]] (1906\u20131990) was a Labour councillor for the [[Monkchester]] ward of [[Newcastle City Council]], and served as the city's Lord Mayor for one year in 1981-2.<ref>https://www.newcastle.gov.uk/sites/default/files/wwwfileroot/your-council-and-democracy/councillors-and-democracy/lord_mayors_and_sheriffs_1974_to_date_1.pdf</ref>\n\nHis mother Marion Marcelline Abrahams was a concert hall violinist for the Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref> and a Labour councillor in Newcastle <ref>https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-jewish-chronicle/20071130/textview</ref>. Abrahams was educated at Ascham House preparatory school, now Newcastle School for Boys in Gosforth, and Rutherford Grammar School.  In 1977, Mohammed Ali paid a visit to the Abrahams family home in Gosforth, where his 105-year-old Grandmother Annie Abrahams chatted to him about the underprivileged <ref>https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/discover-how-muhammad-ali-dropped-11439578</ref>.  In July 1979, he accompanied his Grandmother aged 107 to meet the Queen at Buckingham Palace.\n\n==Political career==\n\nAbrahams was a councillor for the Labour Party on [[Tyne and Wear]] County Council for six years from 1979 to 1983 <ref name=\"channel4.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/domestic_politics/who+is+david+abrahams/1105647.html|title=Who is David Abrahams? - Channel 4 News|website=www.channel4.com}}</ref>, and voted to bring the Nissan plant to Sunderland.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref>\nHe was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Richmond (Yorks) (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond, Yorkshire]] in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] but stood down after a failed deselection attempt by some members of the local party.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/archive/</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/nov/28/uk.partyfunding3|title=Profile: David Abrahams|first=Martin|last=Wainwright|date=28 November 2007|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\">{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hJc8afOZV0QC&pg=PA8&dq=abrahams,+david+martin&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VIMXU6LuEYabtAbS9IGgDw&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=abrahams,+david+martin&f=false|title=The Palgrave Dictionary of Anglo-Jewish History|first1=William D.|last1=Rubinstein|first2=Michael|last2=Jolles|first3=Hilary L.|last3=Rubinstein|date=22 February 2011|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|via=Google Books}}</ref>  In 1997 he was unsuccessful in his attempt at selection for the seat of [[Wansbeck]] near Newcastle.<ref name=\"channel4.com\"/>\n\nA close associate of [[Tony Blair]] and [[Lord Levy]] during the [[New Labour]]-era,<ref name=\"abrah\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/1571209/David-Abrahams-glory-days-as-Blair-ally.html|title=David Abrahams' glory days as Blair ally|date=2 December 2007|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Abrahams was associated with a number of Jewish and pro-Israel groups such as the [[Trade Union Friends of Israel]], the [[Community Security Trust]], the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and [[Academic Friends of Israel]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAbrahams faced high-profile media accusations in 2007 that he had secretly made \u00a3630,000 in donations to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7123236.stm|title=Abrahams makes proxy donor claim|date=1 December 2007|work=BBC News}}</ref> by channelling the donations through four different individuals in what was thought to have been a breach of the electoral law on transparent disclosure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7114500.stm|title=David Abrahams and Labour donations row|date=2 December 2007|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The Donorgate scandal put pressure on then Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] who set up an internal enquiry, although no report has ever been published.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/1570859/Hunt-for-mystery-benefactor-in-Gordon-Browns-donations-scandal.html|title=Hunt for 'mystery benefactor' in Gordon Brown's donations scandal|last=Winnett|first=Robert|date=29 November 2007|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref> Abrahams was subsequently cleared of any wrongdoing by the police, according to a statement issued by his solicitor Louis Charalambous, a partner with the London law firm Simons Muirhead and Burton, in April 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/apr/28/justice.ukcrime|title=Police clear donor Abrahams|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=28 April 2008|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC spotlighted Abrahams in their 'Political Lives' series in February 2014, detailing his life's work.<ref name=\"Hunt\">{{cite news|last=Hunt|first=Alex|title=Political Lives: David Abrahams|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867|accessdate=28 February 2014|publisher=BBC|date=17 February 2014}}</ref> In the BBC interview footage he stated that \"I've been active politically all my life, still am and still taking an active interest in Labour \u2013 these things don't go away. But it's not the be all and end all, being in the Commons \u2013 people have still got the qualities, got the skills, still got the talent and use them in different directions.\"<ref name=\"Hunt\"/>\n\nIn April 2016, following high-profile remarks made by a Labour MP [[Naz Shah]] and the former [[Mayor of London]], [[Ken Livingstone]], Abrahams said that he would no longer financially support the Labour party, claiming it was becoming increasingly [[Antisemitism|anti-semitic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/north-east-labour-donor-said-11259541|title=North East Labour donor said he will give no cash to the party after anti-Semitism scandal|first=Sean|last=Seddon|date=28 April 2016|website=nechronicle}}</ref> In an article for the Guardian he accused the hard left of perverting the principles of social justice and liberal, progressive politics. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/30/labour-rediscover-liberal-values</ref> It has been claimed that he ended his Labour Party membership in late March 2018 because Labour under [[Jeremy Corbyn]] had failed to tackle the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harpin|first=Lee|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/major-jewish-labour-donor-explains-why-he-has-quit-the-party-1.461586|title=Major Jewish Labour donor explains why he has quit the party|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref> However, Abrahams was active in voicing his concerns about the candidates for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leadership election 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Abrahams|first=David|url=https://twitter.com/davidabrahams8/status/1223791592177373184|title=Criticism of Labour Leader Candidates|date=2  Feb 2020|accessdate=6 Feb 2020}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Other Interests==\n\nAbrahams is a [[Freeman of the City of London]].\n\nIn 2010 it was reported that Abrahams had met senior Hamas officials including Palestinian Legislative Council speaker Aziz Dwaik<ref>https://www.thejc.com/news/israel/david-abrahams-meets-hamas-1.13585</ref> and had appeared to wrest a significant change in tone from the Palestinian leadership. He indicated that Hamas officials were prepared to accept \u2013 but not necessarily recognise \u2013 the existence of Israel, and they would be prepared to nullify the part of the Hamas charter that calls for the obliteration of Israel.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/jan/31/david-abrahams-interview</ref>\n\nHe became Vice President of Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) in 2010<ref>https://rusi.org/rusi-news/new-rusi-council</ref>, and subsequently its first global ambassador.  He serves on the Advisory Board of the Global Diplomatic Forum.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\nIn 2013 it was reported that he had donated two tranches of \u00a3250,000 to found a chair in International Politics of the Middle East at [[Warwick University]] from 2005.<ref>https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/labour-donors-cheques-warwick-university-3105529</ref>\n\nHe has also served as Vice-Chairman of the [[Jewish Labour Movement]], Acting Director of Labour Friends of Israel and on the Executive of the Trade Union Friends of Israel.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn 2010, it was reported that used to support \"more than 70 charitable and voluntary organisations, including male cancer research charity 'Every Man Alive'\".<ref name=\"thejc.com\"/>\n\nAbrahams' Twitter page is @davidabrahams 8, where he describes himself as \"working for peace in the Middle East and prosperity in the North East (UK)\".\n\nAbrahams has been an active supporter of peace initiatives in the Middle East. His diplomatic efforts in many Middle East countries brought him into contact with Yasser Arafat as well as Hamas and other leaders establishing grounds for ongoing dialogue.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\nSince 1968, he has been involved North East Prisons After Care Society (NEPACS).  He is currently a trustee and Board Member.\nHe is a former founder and Vice Chair of North East Alzheimer\u2019s Society and was for many years National Director of The Campaign For Pensioner Poverty.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref> He served for twelve years as a trustee and on the executive of The Council for Christians and Jews, becoming their Director of Parliamentary Affairs.<ref>http://www.gdforum.org/our-board</ref>\n\n==Business==\nAbrahams founded the \u201cLondon Girl\u201d group of fashion shops and a chain of hotels in the north east.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25869867</ref>\nIn 2009, Abrahams obtained planning permission to build a 540-acre business park, near Bowburn, outside Durham, with onsite connectivity to the main Edinburgh-London railway line and off Junction 61 on the A1(M). <ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4398717.go-ahead-1bn-durham-green-business-park/</ref> He said he would donate the profits from building the business park to \u201ccauses he has supported in the past\u201d.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4123635.abrahams-ill-give-profits-charity/</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Abrahams was reported to be in  talks with 15 potential tenants for a 540-acre site on the edge of Durham.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/jan/31/david-abrahams-interview|title=Labour donor David Abrahams' gift to the north-east|date=31 January 2010|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>He was subsequently reported to be selling the site.<ref> http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wear/8517543.stm</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was reported that the Integra 61 project on the site would include industrial units, offices, a hotel, shops, gym, care home, pub and GP surgery. Persimmon Homes obtained permission to build up to 270 houses on the site.<ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/northdurham/17186008.details-emerge-170-house-development-integra-61-bowburn/</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that Amazon had taken a warehouse of almost 2 million square feet at the site from new owner Tritax Big Box REIT plc. <ref>https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/business/17496504.new-contractor-announced-integra-61-set-house-huge-amazon-warehouse/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abrahams, David}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Abrahams_(businessman)"}
